{"id":"https://genegraph.clinicalgenome.org/r/40bd98e7-d0da-4a12-97f6-fccd5ee791c8v1.0","type":"EvidenceStrengthAssertion","dc:description":"Variants in *H1-4* were first reported in relation to syndromic intellectual disability (also known as Rahman syndrome) in 2017 (Tatton-Brown et al., PMID: 28475857). Affected individuals present with mild to severe intellectual disability associated with a distinctive facial appearance. Other clinical features include hypotonia, behavioral issues (including autism spectrum disorder or autistic features), cryptorchidism, brain MRI abnormalities, abnormal dentition, cardiac anomalies, skeletal anomalies, and hypothyroidism (PMID: 31400068). Increased growth, reported in the initial description, was not observed in larger cohorts, although macrocephaly is common (PMID: 31447100). \n\n\nNumerous unique frameshift variants in the C-terminal domain of *H1-4* have been reported, with all of the variants occurring *de novo*. This curation includes variants in 8 probands in 4 publications (PMIDs: 2847585, 2938384, 33086257, 34788807). More evidence is available in the literature, but the maximum score for genetic evidence (12 points) has been reached. \n\n*H1-4* encodes histone H1.4, a member of the linker histone family that contributes to higher-order chromatin folding. This gene-disease relationship is supported by functional alterations in both patient and non-patient cells (PMIDs: 31447100, 34788807). The C-terminal frameshift variants result in stable truncated proteins that disrupt chromatin condensation and are associated with a specific methylation pattern (PMID: 31447100). The mechanism of disease has been postulated to be a dominant negative effect or gain of function (PMIDs: 31447100, 34788807).\n\n\nIn summary, there is definitive evidence supporting the relationship between *H1-4* and syndromic intellectual disability. This classification was approved by the ClinGen Intellectual Disability and Autism Gene Curation Expert 